	abstract = {{PURPOSE}: Under the direction of the Association of Program Directors in Vascular Surgery, a survey was mailed to vascular surgery residents ({VSRs}), general surgery chief residents ({GS}-{CRs}), and fourth-year medical students ({MSs}) to better define reasons why trainees do and do not choose vascular surgery as a career.
{METHODS}: Questionnaires were mailed to all accredited {VSR} programs and their associated {GS} programs in the United States and Canada in 2001 (survey 1) and in 2003 (survey 2) and to 2 medical schools with {VSR} programs in 2001. A total of 197 {VSRs}, 169 {GS}-{CRs}, and 78 {MSs} responded (overall program response rate of 78\% for {VSRs}, 46\% for {GSRs}, 20\% for {MSs}). A scoring system was assigned, with 1.0 the least important and 5.0 the most important reasons to choose or not choose vascular surgery.
